<p>The <code>continue</code> tag transforms a stored sequence.</p>

<h2>Store and Transform Sequence</h2>
<pre>{open}sequence 5, push='mySeq'{close}
{open}continue add=10{close}
{open}pull:mySeq{close} {open}$sequence{close} {open}/pull:mySeq{close}</pre>
<p>Original 1-5, after adding 10:</p>
{sequence 5, push='mySeq'}
{resume add=10}
<p>{pull:mySeq} {$sequence} {/pull:mySeq}</p>

<h2>Multiple Transformations</h2>
<pre>{open}sequence 5, push='nums'{close}
{open}continue add=100{close}
{open}continue reverse{close}
{open}pull:nums{close} {open}$sequence{close} {open}/pull:nums{close}</pre>
<p>After add=100 and reverse:</p>
{sequence 5, push='nums'}
{resume add=100}
{resume reverse}
<p>{pull:nums} {$sequence} {/pull:nums}</p>

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>Use <code>pull:</code> prefix to avoid naming conflicts with application tags. The continue tag operates on a stored sequence (via <code>push='name'</code>) and applies transformations like add, subtract, reverse, even, odd, etc.</p>
